item.title: Publicis Raises Guidance After Steady Second Quarter
item.description: Publicis now forecasts organic revenue growth of around 5% for 2023, with an operating margin close to 18% after it maintained its pace of growth for the second quarter.

item.title: HelloFresh Hit By Lower Customer Numbers
item.description: Shares in HelloFresh fell after the company flagged a loss in active customers in the second quarter and revised downward its revenue-growth outlook for 2023 despite projecting better-than-expected quarterly adjusted earnings.

item.title: Givaudan Earnings Drop as Volumes Drag
item.description: Givaudan said first-half operating income and adjusted earnings came in below the previous year, and lower volumes caused reduced cost absorption.

item.title: Electrolux Could See Double Digit FY Consensus Earnings Cuts
item.description: Electrolux earnings missed expectations by a wide margin, and although planned divestitures for around SEK10 billion could be seen as a partial silver lining, Citi sees the potential for double digit percentage cuts to 2023 consensus Ebit.

item.title: Oil Inches Higher Following US Stocks Data
item.description: Oil was little changed following the smaller-than-expected drop in U.S. crude stocks.

item.title: Telenor Backs Views After Second-Quarter Beat
item.description: Telenor posted adjusted underlying earnings and revenue above consensus in the second quarter, and said it still expects low to mid-single digit growth in the Nordics for the full year.

item.title: Investors Not Rushing Back to Buy Dollars Despite Small Recovery
item.description: The dollar edged lower as a recovery after sterling’s drop on Wednesday following the U.K. inflation data proved short-lived, showing investors aren’t ready to buy into the U.S. currency yet, UniCredit Research said.

item.title: Electrolux Mulls Divestments as Demand Weakens
item.description: Electrolux posted an unexpected second-quarter net loss of SEK648 million and said it was considering selling its Zanussi brand and other non-core assets to raise capital, as it now expects negative demand in all regions in 2023.

item.title: ABB Profits Rise Despite Weaker Orders
item.description: ABB said its operational earnings rose by a quarter to $1.4 billion despite a slight decline in new orders and forecast 2023 comparable revenue growth of at least 10% and an operational Ebita margin above 16%.

item.title: EasyJet Sees Strong Winter Demand
item.description: EasyJet posted a headline profit of £203 million in the third quarter on higher passenger numbers and reported good booking momentum for winter, with capacity for the December quarter up by more than 15%.

item.title: Anglo American Production Outlook on Track
item.description: Anglo American kept its full-year production guidance after it reported a 11% rise in second-quarter output, reflecting the ramp-up of its Quellaveco copper mine in Peru.

item.title: Spanish Bonds Underperform Pre-Election But Remain Attractive
item.description: Spanish government bonds represent an attractive investment with comparatively low political and moderate fiscal risks, Erste Asset Management said.

item.title: TSMC's Second-Quarter Net Profit Fell 23% on Lower Revenue, Margins
item.description: Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. said its second-quarter net profit fell 23% from a year earlier on lower margins and revenue..

item.title: Nokia Hit by Slowdown in US Spending
item.description: Nokia’s second-quarter net profit fell 29% but came in slightly above forecasts, as macroeconomic uncertainty weighed on sales, while U.S. customers continued to cut spending.

item.title: Two Killed in New Zealand Shooting on Eve of Women's World Cup
item.description: Authorities say the gunman is also dead in the incident at a construction site, several others were injured.

item.title: Volvo Misses Net Consensus, Expects Sales Growth
item.description: Volvo Car reported net profit of SEK3.3 billion in the second quarter, with revenue rising 43%, and forecast a solid double-digit growth in retail sales for the full year.

item.title: Israel's Benjamin Netanyahu on the Rise of the Ultra-Orthodox
item.description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu spoke with Wall Street Journal reporter Dov Lieber about the country’s Ultra-Orthodox in response to their increasing political power in Israel.

item.title: Mining Deploys Innovative Tech to Find Copper, Other EV Metals
item.description: Startups are developing new ways to increase yields and reduce waste, as the search for critical minerals intensifies.

item.title: The Biggest Winners in America's Climate Law: Foreign Companies
item.description: The U.S. is seeking to build domestic supply chains but needs overseas expertise.

item.title: The Hiring Boom Is Hiding a Recession Indicator
item.description: While some economists are optimistic as hiring booms, employees are actually working fewer hours. Usually, reducing working hours has been a reliable sign of incoming layoffs – and a possible recession. WSJ explains what it may mean moving forward.
